   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0363">
               <p>Born in <placeName>Brompton, Yorkshire</placeName>, Cayley was educated at a
                  public school and at nineteen became a clerk in the Prince of Wales&apos;s
                  treasury. For a while he sought advancements, but by <date when="1751">1751</date>
                  turned to religious pursuits. He was drawn to the Tabernacle in
                     <placeName>London</placeName> and its Calvinist Methodism, and soon began
                  preaching in and around <placeName>London</placeName>. About <date when="1756"
                     >1756</date> he came under the influence of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2211.xml"/>James Wheatley</persName>, and soon
                  abandoned his wife—<persName><ref target="/persons/pers0364.xml"/>Sarah (Dyer)
                     Cayley</persName>—and moved to <placeName>Norwich</placeName>. When things fell
                  apart for <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2211.xml"/>Wheatley</persName> in
                     <placeName>Norwich</placeName>, Cayley turned to travel and a series of
                  literary pursuits, until settling at an estate in <placeName>Kingston upon
                     Hull</placeName>. There he occasionally preached in surrounding towns.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
